 :tx/rationale "DOG-FOODING DEEP ASSESSMENT — SESSION 029 (44 tasks executed). This is the most honest account I can give of what it feels like to use braid as an LLM agent building braid itself.\n\nWHAT GENUINELY WORKS (5 things I'd miss if they disappeared):\n\n1. R(t) ROUTING ELIMINATES DECISION PARALYSIS. With 354 open tasks, 'what should I do next?' is paralyzing. R(t) consistently picks the right task. When I closed ST-1, it immediately routed to ST-3. When I closed CTP-1, it routed to CTP-2. The routing feels like a competent project manager who always knows the critical path. This is the single most valuable feature for an agent.\n\n2. TSV OUTPUT IS A FORCE MULTIPLIER. The moment --format tsv went live, my workflow changed. 'braid task list --format tsv | awk' replaced 15-line Python pipelines. I used it dozens of times this session. The 3.75x density improvement is real — I can see 4x more data per token spent.\n\n3. SHORT_TITLE MAKES TASK LISTS USABLE. Before: task titles were 200+ characters of BACKGROUND text. After: activation patterns like 'CTP-3: Demonstration retrieval'. This single change made braid task list go from 'wall of text I skip' to 'table I actually read'. API-as-prompt works.\n\n4. THE OBSERVE→CRYSTALLIZE→TASK PIPELINE PREVENTS SLOPPY THINKING. When I tried to jump straight to implementation (creating TSV tasks without observing the ACP connection), the pipeline forced me to slow down and formalize. The reconciliation failure we diagnosed was BECAUSE I bypassed the pipeline. When I follow it, the quality is measurably higher.\n\n5. SPEC_GRAPH_NEIGHBORS IS ALREADY WORKING. I saw [spec+graph] in the braid observe output — the VAET traversal surfaced connections that keyword search missed. This is the fix for the exact failure mode that triggered the Ambient Reconciliation EPIC."
